gomodel:SYNGO_4092  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig4C-F: Miniature excitatory postsynaptic currents (mEPSC) in presence of 1 μM TTX to abolish action potential driven network activity and 10 μM bicuculline to pharmacologically isolate excitatory (glutamatergic) events showed a 65% reduction in Nrxn2a KO mice compared to WT. The amplitude and decay times of mEPSC were unchanged indicating that the KO perhaps does not grossly affect transmitter quanta and receptors properties.\nFig 4G-H: In order to check if the reduced mEPSC frequency was due to altered synapse density in brain tissue, quantitative electron microscopy was performed. The number of excitatory synapses, the area density of synaptic vesicles, length of synaptic zones, the width of synaptic clefts and the area of synaptic terminals were not altered between Nrxn2A KO and WT suggesting that the differences observed in spontaneous excitatory transmission are not caused by structural defects.\nFig 5A-D: To evaluate if the reduction in mEPSC frequency is caused due to presynaptic mechanisms, paired-pulse facilitation paradigm was conducted. PPF was significantly reduced at most intervals in Nrxn2A-KO neurons.\nFig 5G-H: Quantitative analysis of NMDA/AMPA ratios revealed an almost 25% reduction in Nrxn2α KO neurons as compared to WT.\n\n18/01/2021 Dnyanada: Based on the reduction in NMDAR-dependent decay time and NMDAR-mediated responses in Nrxn2α KO excitatory synapses, the term \"regulation of postsynaptic neurotransmitter receptor activity\" was used.. Experimental description: Nrxn2α KO mice were generated as described in Missler et al., 2003." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2916-7616" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2021-01-18" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4092" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

